node.text: @xo.monee If they used their sexuality as a major focus of their life, discussing it and respecting it is fine. Many LGBT icons have passed away, but their legacy is built around how they used their queer identity to help those of us in the community now. Honoring that is part of honoring them. But a young girl who was killed for being Jewish? Who may or may not have been questioning her attraction? There is no need. Her story was written as a testament to the horror of the Holocaust, and that is what needs to be honored.

To be completely honest, while reading Anne Frank’s Diary I never really noticed/payed attention to her sexuality? (I don’t want to sound disrespectful) even as a bisexual person who loves LGBTQ+ historical figures, I agree that Anne is not a LGBTQ+ historical figure. Her sexuality should not be overshadowing the central story within her diary, the story that she wanted the world to know; The Nazis are coming for us, not because we committed crimes, but because were Jewish.
